		<title type="html"><![CDATA[First Public Working Draft: CSS Grid Layout Module Level 2]]></title>
		<link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://www.w3.org/blog/news/archives/6818" />
		<id>https://www.w3.org/blog/news/?p=6818</id>
		<updated>2018-02-22T10:49:17Z</updated>
		<published>2018-02-06T08:06:02Z</published>
		<category scheme="https://www.w3.org/blog/news" term="Publication" /><category scheme="https://www.w3.org/blog/news" term="Web Design and Applications" />		<summary type="html"><![CDATA[The CSS Working Group has published a First Public Working Draft of CSS Grid Layout Module Level 2. This CSS module defines a two-dimensional grid-based layout system, optimized for user interface design. In the grid layout model, the children of a grid container can be positioned into arbitrary slots in a predefined flexible or fixed-size [&#8230;]]]></summary>
		<content type="html" xml:base="https://www.w3.org/blog/news/archives/6818"><![CDATA[<p>The <a href="https://www.w3.org/Style/CSS/members">CSS Working Group</a> has published a First Public Working Draft of <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/2018/WD-css-grid-2-20180206/">CSS Grid Layout Module Level 2</a>. This CSS module defines a two-dimensional grid-based layout system, optimized for user interface design. In the grid layout model, the children of a grid container can be positioned into arbitrary slots in a predefined flexible or fixed-size layout grid. Level 2 expands Grid by adding “subgrid” capabilities for nested grids to participate in the sizing of their parent grids; and aspect-ratio–controlled gutters.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/CSS/">CSS</a> is a language for describing the rendering of structured documents (such as HTML and XML) on screen, on paper, in speech, etc.</p>
]]></content>
